1. Replace &lt;p&gt; elements styled to look like headings with proper &lt;h1&gt; to &lt;h6&gt; heading elements.
 2. Use CSS to style the heading elements as needed to match the design.


 Example:


 Instead of:
 &lt;p style="font-size: 1.2em; font-weight: bold;"&gt;Introduction&lt;/p&gt;


 Use:
 &lt;h2&gt;Introduction&lt;/h2&gt;


 Then, use CSS to style the &lt;h2&gt; element:
 h2 { font-size: 1.2em; font-weight: bold; }

1. Use relative units (em, rem, %) for font sizes instead of pixels.
 2. Use style sheets to control text appearance, separating content from presentation.
 3. Allow users to override author styles using browser settings or custom stylesheets.
 4. Ensure sufficient contrast between text and background colors, and provide options to adjust them.
 5. Avoid using images of text. Use real text instead.
 6. Test the website with different font sizes, line heights, and font families to ensure content remains readable and usable.
 7. Use viewport meta tag to control layout on mobile devices.
 Example:
 font-size: 1.2em;
 line-height: 1.5;
 color: #333;
 background-color: #fff;

1. Identify elements with scrollable content (e.g., elements with CSS `overflow: auto` or `overflow: scroll`).
 2. Check if these elements are focusable. If not, add `tabindex="0"` to make them focusable.
 3. Implement keyboard event listeners for arrow keys (Up, Down, Left, Right), Page Up, and Page Down.
 4. Within the event listeners, programmatically adjust the `scrollTop` or `scrollLeft` properties of the element to scroll the content accordingly. For example:


 ```javascript
 const scrollableElement = document.getElementById('myScrollableDiv');
 scrollableElement.addEventListener('keydown', function(event) {
  if (event.key === 'ArrowDown') {
  scrollableElement.scrollTop += 10; // Scroll down
  } else if (event.key === 'ArrowUp') {
  scrollableElement.scrollTop -= 10; // Scroll up
  }
 });
 ```
 5. Test thoroughly with a keyboard to ensure smooth and complete scrolling functionality.

1. **Provide a mechanism to disable the shortcut:** Offer users a setting to turn off the keyboard shortcut.
  ```html
  <label for="disableShortcut">Disable Shortcut:</label>
  <input type="checkbox" id="disableShortcut" name="disableShortcut">
  ```
  ```javascript
  const disableShortcutCheckbox = document.getElementById('disableShortcut');
  disableShortcutCheckbox.addEventListener('change', (event) => {
  if (event.target.checked) {
  // Code to disable the shortcut
  } else {
  // Code to enable the shortcut
  }
  });
  ```
 2. **Allow remapping of the shortcut:** Let users change the keys used for the shortcut.
  ```html
  <label for="shortcutKey">Remap Shortcut:</label>
  <input type="text" id="shortcutKey" name="shortcutKey">
  ```
 3. **Restrict activation to focused components:** Ensure the shortcut only works when the relevant component has focus. Use `addEventListener` with appropriate focus and blur handling.
  ```javascript
  const myElement = document.getElementById('myElement');
  myElement.addEventListener('focus', () => {
  document.addEventListener('keydown', handleKeyDown);
  });
  myElement.addEventListener('blur', () => {
  document.removeEventListener('keydown', handleKeyDown);
  });


  function handleKeyDown(event) {
  if (event.key === 'a') { // Example shortcut 'a'
  // Perform action
  }
  }
  ```

1. Remove all `<blink>` elements from your HTML.
 2. Replace the blinking effect with CSS animations or JavaScript solutions.
 3. Ensure the animations can be paused or stopped by the user.
 Example:
 Instead of `<blink>Important Message</blink>` use:
 ```html
 <span class="blinking">Important Message</span>
 ```
 ```css
 @keyframes blinker {
  50% { opacity: 0; }
 }
 .blinking {
  animation: blinker 1s linear infinite;
 }
 ```
 Add a button to pause the animation:
 ```html
 <button onclick="pauseAnimation()">Pause Animation</button>
 ```
 ```javascript
 function pauseAnimation() {
  let elements = document.getElementsByClassName('blinking');
  for (let i = 0; i < elements.length; i++) {
  elements[i].style.animationPlayState = 'paused';
  }
 }
 ```

1. Remove all `<marquee>` elements from the HTML code.
 2. Replace the functionality with CSS animations or JavaScript. 
 3. Ensure any animations have controls to pause, stop, and adjust speed.
 Example: Instead of `<marquee>Scrolling text</marquee>`, use CSS animation:
 ```html
 <div class="scrolling-text">Scrolling text</div>
 ```
 ```css
 .scrolling-text {
  animation: scroll 10s linear infinite;
 }
 @keyframes scroll {
  from { transform: translateX(100%); }
  to { transform: translateX(-100%); }
 }
 ```
 Add pause/play button using javascript to control animation speed.

1. **Remove the `<meta http-equiv="refresh">` tag:** Locate and remove any `<meta http-equiv="refresh" content="...">` tags from the `<head>` section of your HTML. 
 2. **Implement Server-Side Redirects:** Use server-side redirects (e.g., HTTP 301 or 302 redirects) if you need to redirect users to a different page. These redirects are handled by the server and do not rely on the client-side rendering of a meta tag. For example, in PHP: `header("Location: new_page.html"); exit;`
 3. **Use JavaScript with User Control:** If a client-side redirect is necessary, use JavaScript but provide a clear warning and a way for the user to prevent the redirect. For example:
  ```html
  <p>You will be redirected in <span id="countdown">5</span> seconds. <a href="new_page.html">Click here to go now.</a></p>
  <script>
  let count = 5;
  const countdownEl = document.getElementById('countdown');
  const redirectLink = document.querySelector('a[href="new_page.html"]');
  const intervalId = setInterval(() => {
  count--;
  countdownEl.textContent = count;
  if (count <= 0) {
  clearInterval(intervalId);
  window.location.href = redirectLink.href; // Or use window.location.replace if you don't want the user to be able to go back
  }
  }, 1000);
  </script>
  ```
  Include an option to cancel the redirect using `clearInterval(intervalId)`. Give the user a button: `<button onclick='clearInterval(intervalId); alert("Redirect cancelled.");'>Cancel Redirect</button>`

1. Implement session management that preserves form data or user state before requiring re-authentication.
 2. Use server-side session storage or browser local storage (with appropriate security measures) to temporarily save the data.
 3. Upon successful re-authentication, automatically repopulate the form fields with the saved data.
 4. Alternatively, redirect the user back to the exact point in the process where they were interrupted before re-authentication was required.
 5. Clearly inform the user about the upcoming session timeout and the re-authentication process beforehand.
 Example: Using server-side session:
 ```php
 session_start();
 $_SESSION['form_data'] = $_POST;
 //After re-authentication
 $_POST = $_SESSION['form_data'];
 ```

1. Implement a timeout warning mechanism that activates a reasonable amount of time (e.g., 2 minutes) before the session expires. Display a clear and easily understandable message to the user.
 2. Provide an option for the user to extend the session with a simple action (e.g., clicking a button labeled 'Extend Session').
 3. If extending the session isn't possible, ensure that data is automatically saved at regular intervals (e.g., every minute) and that the user is notified that their data is being saved. Consider providing an explicit 'Save' button.
 4. If the user doesn't respond to the warning or the session expires, clearly inform the user what happened and, if possible, how to recover their data or resume their session. Provide clear instructions on how to log back in or retrieve saved work.
 Example:
 ```html
 <div id="timeoutWarning" style="display:none;">
  <p>Your session will expire in 2 minutes. Click below to extend your session.</p>
  <button id="extendSession">Extend Session</button>
 </div>
 ```
 ```javascript
 // Example JavaScript to show the warning and handle session extension
 var timeoutWarning = document.getElementById('timeoutWarning');
 var extendSessionButton = document.getElementById('extendSession');
 var timeout;


 function startTimeout() {
  timeout = setTimeout(function() {
  timeoutWarning.style.display = 'block';
  }, 118 * 60 * 1000); // 118 minutes
 }


 extendSessionButton.addEventListener('click', function() {
  clearTimeout(timeout);
  timeoutWarning.style.display = 'none';
  startTimeout(); // Restart the timeout
 });


 startTimeout();
 ```

1. **Check Touch Target Size:** Inspect the CSS dimensions of touch targets to ensure they meet the minimum size requirements (24x24 CSS pixels, or 44x44 CSS pixels). Use browser developer tools to examine the computed size and spacing of elements.
 2. **Increase Target Size:** If targets are too small, increase their width and height using CSS. For example:
  ```css
  .touch-target {
  min-width: 44px;
  min-height: 44px;
  }
  ```
 3. **Add Spacing:** If increasing the target size is not feasible, add sufficient spacing around the target using CSS margins or padding. Ensure that the spacing is at least 1 CSS pixel.
  ```css
  .touch-target {
  margin: 4px;
  }
  ```
 4. **Consider Path-Based definition:** If a path-based definition is used for the touch target, make sure the path encompasses a sufficient area to allow for easy interaction. If not, increase area.
 5. **Test on Mobile Devices:** Test the touch target on a variety of mobile devices and screen sizes to ensure that it remains accessible and usable.
